        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP Messaging</strong> was a Google Business Profile feature that let customers send text messages to a business directly from Google Search and Maps listings. Google <strong>discontinued the feature in July 2024</strong> due to low adoption and inconsistent response quality. Businesses now rely on click-to-call, booking links, and website chat to replace the lost lead channel.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Status</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip err">Retired</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO · GBP</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Discontinued</div>
            <div class="tms-value">July 2024</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">GBP Messaging is worth understanding even after retirement because thousands of local businesses still have workflows built around it, and the replacement stack decides whether those leads survive.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What was GBP Messaging?</h2>
        <p>GBP Messaging (also called Google Business Messages) was a real-time text channel embedded inside a business's Google Business Profile. A "Message" button appeared alongside "Call" and "Directions" on the listing. Customers tapped it and started a text thread from Google Search or Maps — no phone call, no form fill, no context switch.</p>
        <p>The feature launched broadly in 2017, matured into the GBP dashboard through 2020-2023, and was retired by Google in July 2024. Google announced the wind-down citing two problems: low business adoption relative to other communication channels, and inconsistent response quality that hurt user experience on the Search results page.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance on retirement</div>
          <p>Google's official guidance directs businesses to <strong>click-to-call, booking links, and website chat</strong> as replacements. There is no announced plan to reintroduce messaging, though Google continues testing new communication surfaces inside Search.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP Messaging mattered</h2>
        <p>When the feature was live, it solved four specific problems local businesses face:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Reduced friction for text-first customers.</strong> Younger demographics and busy professionals often prefer texting over phone calls. Messaging captured intent that would otherwise abandon the listing.</li>
          <li><strong>Response tracking built into the platform.</strong> Google monitored average response time and could deactivate messaging for slow responders — a forcing function for customer service quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Extended-hours lead capture.</strong> Customers could message outside business hours and receive a reply the next morning, without the business paying for a 24/7 answering service.</li>
          <li><strong>Zero-click contact.</strong> The message button appeared on the SERP itself, so a customer never had to click through to a website or dial a number. Every step removed from the funnel lifted conversion.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP Messaging worked</h2>
        <p>The mechanics were simple by design. A business owner activated messaging inside the GBP dashboard. A "Message" button appeared on the listing. Customers tapped it, wrote a message, and the thread landed in the GBP mobile app or web interface. Google expected a response within 24 hours and tracked the average.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The customer flow</span><br>
          Customer searches <span class="uf-old">"emergency plumber near me"</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Sees business listing with <span class="uf-new">[Call] [Directions] [Message]</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Taps <span class="uf-new">Message</span> · types <span class="uf-old">"burst pipe, need help tonight"</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Business receives push notification in GBP app<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Business replies · thread continues in-app<br>
          <span class="uf-status">Response time tracked by Google</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Automated welcome messages</h3>
        <p>Businesses could set an auto-response that fired the moment a thread opened. Common templates included office hours, expected response time, and a link to book online. Well-configured welcome messages doubled as a soft lead-qualifier.</p>

        <h3>Response-time enforcement</h3>
        <p>If a business's average response time crept above 24 hours across multiple threads, Google could deactivate the messaging button automatically. Reactivation required proving consistent responsiveness — usually across a two-week window.</p>

        <h2 id="types">GBP Messaging vs the alternatives Google now recommends</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
